# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1794-state-of-the-union-address
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from December 15, 1788 to January 7, 1789, under the new Constitution ratified in 1788.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] George Washington was unanimously elected for the first of his two terms as president and John Adams became the first vice president.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] This was the only U.S. presidential election that spanned two calendar years without a contingent election and the first national presidential election in American history.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under the Articles of Confederation, which were ratified in 1781, the United States had no head of state.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The executive function of government remained with the legislative similar to countries that use a parliamentary system.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Federal power, strictly limited, was reserved to the Congress of the Confederation whose "President of the United States in Congress Assembled" was also chair of the Committee of the States which aimed to fulfill a function similar to that of the modern Cabinet.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution created the offices of President and Vice President, fully separating these offices from Congress.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution established an Electoral College, based on each state's congressional representation, in which each elector would cast two votes for two candidates, a procedure modified in 1804 by the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] States had varying methods for choosing presidential electors.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In five states, the state legislature chose electors.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The other six chose electors through some form involving a popular vote, though in only two states did the choice depend directly on a statewide vote.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The enormously popular Washington was distinguished as the former Commander of the Continental Army during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] After he agreed to come out of retirement, he was elected with ease unanimously; Washington did not select a running mate as that concept was not yet developed.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No formal political parties existed, though an informally organized consistent difference of opinion had already manifested between Federalists and Anti-Federalists.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, the contest for the vice-presidency was open.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Jefferson predicted that a popular Northern leader such as Governor John Hancock of Massachusetts or John Adams, a former minister to Great Britain who had represented Massachusetts in Congress, would be elected vice president.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-Federalists leaders such as Patrick Henry, who did not run, and George Clinton, who had opposed ratification of the Constitution, also represented potential choices.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] All 69 electors present cast one vote for Washington, making his election unanimous.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 34 electoral votes and the vice presidency.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 35 electoral votes were split among 10 candidates, including John Jay, who finished third with nine electoral votes.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Three states were ineligible to participate in the election: New York's legislature did not choose electors on time, and North Carolina and Rhode Island had not yet ratified the constitution.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was inaugurated in New York City on April 30, 1789, 57 days after the First Congress convened.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Both factions supported Washington for president.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Limited, primitive political campaigning occurred in states and localities where swaying public opinion might have mattered.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Maryland, a state with a statewide popular vote, unofficial parties campaigned locally, advertising.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No nomination process existed at the time of planning, and thus, the framers of the Constitution presumed that Washington would be elected unopposed.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Another uncertainty was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained no definite job description beyond being the president's designated successor and presiding over the Senate.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution stipulated that the position would be awarded to the runner-up in the presidential election.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because Washington was from Virginia, then the largest state, many assumed that electors would choose a vice president from a northern state.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Minister to France Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams and John Hancock, both from Massachusetts, to be the top contenders.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson suggested John Jay, John Rutledge, and Virginian James Madison as other possible candidates.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received 34 electoral votes, one short of a majority – because the Constitution did not require an outright majority in the Electoral College prior to ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to elect a runner-up as vice president, Adams was elected to that post.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, the states differed in their interpretations of this procedure and of the relevant portions of the new Constitution.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] New Hampshire and Massachusetts held a popular vote for their presidential electors alongside the elections for their representatives in the new Congress, on December 15 and December 18, respectively.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In these two states, the legislatures ultimately chose the electors based on the voting results on the appointed day, January 7.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Delaware, Maryland, Pennsylvania, and Virginia, the electors were chosen directly by the popular vote on January 7.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Connecticut, Georgia, and South Carolina, the electors were appointed by the legislature alone on January 7, while in New Jersey the governor and council selected them on that day.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The legislature in New York was unable to agree on a method for choosing the electors before January 7, and so the state could not appoint any electors.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voter turnout comprised a low single-digit percentage of the adult population.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Though all states allowed some rudimentary form of popular vote, only six ratifying states allowed any form of popular vote specifically for presidential electors.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most states only white men, and in many only those who owned property, could vote.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Free black men could vote in four Northern states, and women could vote in New Jersey until 1804.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In some states, there was a nominal religious test for voting.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Massachusetts and Connecticut, the Congregational Church was established, supported by taxes.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voting was hampered by poor communications and infrastructure and the labor demands imposed by farming.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Two months passed after the election before the votes were counted and Washington was notified that he had been elected president.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington spent eight days traveling from Virginia to New York for the inauguration.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Congress took twenty-eight days to assemble.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As the electors were selected, politics intruded, and the process was not free of rumors and intrigue.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, Hamilton aimed to ensure that Adams did not inadvertently tie Washington in the electoral vote.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Also, Federalists spread rumors that Anti-Federalists plotted to elect Richard Henry Lee or Patrick Henry president, with George Clinton as vice president.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, Clinton received only three electoral votes.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Several respected sources, including the Biographical Directory of the United States Congress and the Political Graveyard, show this individual to be James Armstrong of Pennsylvania.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, primary sources, such as the Senate Journal, list only Armstrong's name, not his state.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Skeptics observe that Armstrong received his single vote from a Georgia elector.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Early presidential elections used a form of plurality block voting that preceded the widespread adoption of the general ticket.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, voters elected each member of the Electoral College individually; electors nominated by the same political party often received differing numbers of votes as a consequence of voter rolloff, split-ticket voting, or electoral fusion.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most cases, this table calculates the popular vote of each state based on the votes for the leading Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors in each constituent county or township.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In states where the electors were chosen from single-member districts, all votes for Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors are counted.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Most townships in New Hampshire are missing data for this election; the figure shown is the result for the leading Federalist elector statewide.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because published compilations of the election results are missing labels for many electors, the estimate presented here is incomplete.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 69 participating electors, each cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the remaining candidates, only Adams, Jay, and Hancock received votes from more than one state; with 34 votes, Adams finished second behind only Washington, and by virtue of which fact was elected vice president.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Control of the bicameral New York State Legislature was divided following ratification of the federal constitution, and lawmakers could not reach an agreement to appoint electors for the forthcoming presidential contest.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The fight to ratify the United States Constitution was still fresh in the memories of the legislators, and the Anti-Federalists were resentful for having been forced by events to accept the constitution without amendments.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Bills to govern the selection of electors were proposed in each house and rejected by the other, leading to an impasse.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The deadlock still stood on January 7, 1789, the last day for electors to be chosen by the states, and New York thus failed to appoint the eight electors allocated to it by the constitution.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution, in Article II, Section 1, provided that the state legislatures should decide the manner in which their Electors were chosen.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The state of union is an address, in the United States, given by the president to a joint session of Congress, the United States House of Representatives and United States Senate.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The United States constitution requires the president "from time to time give to the Congress Information of the State of the Union." Today the state of the union address is given as a speech, though this is not a requirement of the constitution.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] George Washington chose to address the Congress in a speech annually; on October 25, 1791, he gave his third speech.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] A major concern at the time was the raising of taxes, as Congress were arguing whether they had the constitutional power to do so.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Revenues for the Federal Government were at that time mostly collected on import duties.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Alexander Hamilton, the then Secretary of the Treasury, felt these had been raised to as high a level as was reasonable, and a new income stream was necessary.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Before the speech, Congress had been debating where to put the capital.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Finally, through a deal made between Alexander Hamilton, James Madison, and Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson, they came to a conclusion.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] This deal is known as the Compromise of 1790.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] At the time the U.S. was in possession of the original thirteen colonies, along with the land gained in the Treaty of Paris.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The Treaty of Paris ended the revolutionary war; in it, America was granted territory as far west as the Mississippi River.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Known as the year of "Great Immigration" 1788 was the year many Americans moved west.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] On October 18, 1790, the Ohio tribe defeated an expedition of American troops near Fort Wayne, Indiana; this signified the beginning of the hostilities in the North West territory.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] On March 30, 1791, construction of the Knoxville Road began, linking to the Wilderness Road and to Knoxville.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The road opened up more frontier area for settlements.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] In September 1791, there was much hostility in Ohio territory; this caused Americans to build forts at Hamilton, St.Clair, Jefferson, Greenville and Recovery.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] At the time the Census Act had been in place for just over a year and a half.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The act called for a routine census of the United States, and was passed by Congress on March 1, 1790.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He acknowledged that there had been some "degree of discontent" about the Whiskey Tax, and that it was not perfect, but he was going to keep it anyway.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He said "revision of the provision will be found advisable." The Whiskey tax was one Hamilton wanted enacted as part of a funding system for the new country.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He says that the debt has been mostly dealt with, but there might be a few things that still need to be paid off and he urges the House of Representatives to pay off any lingering debts, and there will be exact numbers coming to them soon.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] "The part of the debt of the United States which remains unsubscribed will naturally engage your further deliberation," Washington is saying the House of Representatives must talk further on the debt that has not yet been dealt with.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Washington briefly mentions the "completion of the census of the inhabitants," he is talking about the Census of 1790.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He says that "the present population of the United States borders on 4,000,000 persons".
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The number was 3,929,625 according to the 1790 Census.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] At the end of the speech he comments on "the militia, the post office and post roads, the mint, weights and measures, a provision for the sale of the vacant lands of the United States." Washington wants to send militia to particularly vulnerable places in the US, as they are a new country.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He says that the United States must have "systematic and solid arrangements, exposed as little as possible to the hazards of fortuitous circumstances." He beliefs that there must be more post offices and roads, to create unity with in the country.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] As well to make sure that there is no :misrepresentation and misconception" of the "laws and proceedings of the Government." He then remarks that there is a scarcity of smaller American change and that there must be more put into place.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Washington then goes on to say that the wright and measures of the country must be uniform and conducive to public convenience.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Washington spent a good deal of the speech trying to convince the Native Americans to become part of the United States, as well as convincing the citizens of the country of the importance of doing so.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He pushed the Senate to ratify the treaties pending before that House with the Cherokees and Six Nations of Indians (Iroquois Confederation).
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He stated that the House needed to act on bills to ensure the financial security of the nation.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] The **1792 State of the Union Address** was delivered by George Washington to Congress on Tuesday, November 6, 1792.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] It was presented in Philadelphia's Congress Hall.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] The president commented on continued incursions by Native Americans into frontier settlements.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] Notably, the address contains mention of the Chickamaugas, a part of the Cherokee tribe that committed multiple incursions in frontiers along the Tennessee River.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] The President noted that the incursions were a violation of the Treaty of Holston.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] Still further to promote and secure these inestimable ends there is nothing which can have a more powerful tendency than the careful cultivation of harmony, combined with a due regard to stability, in the public councils.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 2 to December 5, 1792.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent President George Washington was elected to a second term by a unanimous vote in the electoral college, while John Adams was reelected as vice president.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was essentially unopposed, but Adams faced a competitive re-election against Governor George Clinton of New York.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Electoral rules of the time required each presidential elector to cast two votes without distinguishing which was for president and which for vice president.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The recipient of the most votes would then become president, and the runner-up vice president.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican Party, which had organized in opposition to the policies of Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Hamilton, supported Clinton for the position of vice president.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams, meanwhile, was backed by the Federalist Party in his bid for another term.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Neither party had fully organized, and partisan divisions had not yet solidified.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington received 132 electoral votes, one from each elector.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 77 electoral votes, enough to win re-election.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton finished in third place with 50 electoral votes, taking his home state of New York as well as three Southern states.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Two other candidates won the five remaining electoral votes.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] This election was the first in which each of the original 13 states appointed electors, as did the newly added states of Kentucky and Vermont.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In 1792, presidential elections were still conducted according to the original method established under the U.S.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, each elector cast two votes: the candidate who received the greatest number of votes (so long as they won a majority) became president, while the runner-up became vice president.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Twelfth Amendment would eventually replace this system, requiring electors to cast one vote for president and one vote for vice president, but this change did not take effect until 1804.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because of this, it is difficult to use modern-day terminology to describe the relationship among the candidates in this election.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington is generally held by historians to have run unopposed.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Indeed, the incumbent president enjoyed bipartisan support and received one vote from every elector.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The choice for vice president was more divisive.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist Party threw its support behind the incumbent vice president, John Adams of Massachusetts, while the Democratic-Republican Party backed the candidacy of New York Governor George Clinton.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because few doubted that Washington would receive the greatest number of votes, Adams and Clinton were effectively competing for the vice presidency; under the letter of the law, however, they were technically candidates for president competing against Washington.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Born out of the Anti-Federalist faction that had opposed the Constitution in 1788, the Democratic-Republican Party was the main opposition to the agenda of Treasury Secretary Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] They had no chance of unseating Washington, but hoped to win the vice presidency by defeating the incumbent, Adams.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Many Democratic-Republicans would have preferred to nominate Thomas Jefferson, their ideological leader and Washington's Secretary of State.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, this would have cost them the state of Virginia, as electors were not permitted to vote for two candidates from their home state and Washington was also a Virginian.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton, the Governor of New York and a former anti-Federalist leader, became the party's nominee after he won the backing of Jefferson and James Madison.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton was from an electorally important swing state, and he convinced party leaders that he would be a stronger candidate than another New Yorker, Senator Aaron Burr.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Democratic-Republican leaders met in Philadelphia in October 1792 and selected Clinton as the party's vice presidential candidate.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Madison was at first a Federalist until he opposed the establishment of Hamilton's First Bank of the United States in 1791.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] He formed the Democratic-Republican Party along with Anti-Federalist Thomas Jefferson in 1792.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The elections of 1792 were the first ones in the United States to be contested on anything resembling a partisan basis.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In most states, the congressional elections were recognized in some sense as a "struggle between the Treasury department and the republican interest," to use the words of Jefferson strategist John Beckley.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, the race for governor was fought along these lines.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The candidates were Chief Justice John Jay, a Hamiltonian, and incumbent George Clinton, the party's vice presidential nominee.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Although Washington had been considering retiring, both sides encouraged him to remain in office to bridge factional differences.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was supported by practically all sides throughout his presidency and gained more popularity with the passage of the Bill of Rights.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, the Democratic-Republicans and the Federalists contested the vice-presidency, with incumbent John Adams as the Federalist nominee and George Clinton as the Democratic-Republican nominee.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attacked Clinton for his past association with the anti-Federalists.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Congress counted the electoral results on February 13, 1793, with John Adams opening and reading the votes in his role as President of the Senate.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was re-elected unanimously, receiving one vote from each of the 132 participating electors.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received votes from 77 electors and Clinton 50; the four electors from Kentucky voted for Thomas Jefferson, and one South Carolina elector voted for Aaron Burr.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The distribution of the electoral vote between the four runners-up showed a high degree of party discipline, with only two electors voting contrary to the majority in their state.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received the support of New England, South Carolina, and the Mid-Atlantic states (excepting New York), while Clinton carried New York and most of the South.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Nine of the 15 states eligible to choose representatives to the electoral college did so by a vote of the state legislature; the remaining six employed some form of popular vote.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, complete returns from Maryland, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, and Pennsylvania survive; surviving returns from Virginia are incomplete, and popular vote records from Kentucky are not known to exist.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of the states with complete returns, only Pennsylvania saw real partisan competition; a Federalist electoral slate pledged to Washington and Adams was selected, although one elector voted for Washington and Clinton.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] At the time, party organizations were still in their infancy, and the partisan allegiance of the candidates was not always evident: it is therefore difficult to say whether the Pennsylvania vote for Clinton was an instance of a faithless elector, or an elector voting as pledged.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Elections in this period were vastly different from modern day presidential elections.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The actual presidential candidates were rarely mentioned on tickets and voters were voting for particular electors who were pledged to a particular candidate.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] There was sometimes confusion as to who the particular elector was actually pledged to.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Results are reported as the highest result for an elector for any given faction.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] For example, if three Federalist electors received 100, 50, and 25 votes, Federalist electors would be recorded as having 100 votes.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Confusion surrounding the way results are reported may lead to discrepancies between the sum of all state results and national results.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, the best performing elector candidate for the Eastern District, Thomas Rice, was not selected by the Massachusetts General Court to be an elector.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Rice was a Federalist and his returns have been included into the state total below instead of the second best performing elector candidate.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The totals for Kentucky, Pennsylvania, and Virginia appear to be incomplete.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In several states candidates of unknown affiliation received votes.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The states chose 135 electors, out of whom 132 cast ballots.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] (Two electors from Maryland and one from Vermont were absent and did not vote.) As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Each of the participating electors cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The electors were split on their second choice: Adams received 77 votes to Clinton's 50, enough to secure a second-place finish behind Washington and the vice presidency.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] The **1793 State of the Union Address** was given by George Washington, the first president of the United States.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] It was given in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania at Congress Hall.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] During the address, Washington spoke of Peace through strength.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] He also urged the expansion of the legal code and jurisdiction of the courts in order to enforce the laws of the land.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] The President reported on progress for peace with the Creek and Cherokee tribes and noted that trade with the tribes should be expanded where possible.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1794-state-of-the-union-address] The **1794 State of the Union Address** was delivered by the first president of the United States, George Washington, to a joint session of the 3rd United States Congress on November 19, 1794.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1794-state-of-the-union-address] The speech came in the aftermath of the Whiskey Rebellion, an armed insurrection in the western counties of Pennsylvania against the federal excise tax on whiskey.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1794-state-of-the-union-address] Washington highlighted the failure of peaceful measures, noting that the government's attempts at moderation and reconciliation were misinterpreted as weakness.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1794-state-of-the-union-address] He described how, despite offering pardons and seeking negotiations, the insurrection continued, leading to the deployment of 15,000 militia troops.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1794-state-of-the-union-address] The address also stressed the importance of upholding the Constitution, warning against the dangers posed by lawlessness and sedition.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1794-state-of-the-union-address] Washington praised the militia for their dedication and perseverance, remarking on the "patriotic cooperation" between the federal government and the states.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1794-state-of-the-union-address] In addition to addressing the Whiskey Rebellion, Washington briefly touched upon other issues, including relations with Native American tribes and the nation's foreign policy, particularly the need to avoid entanglements in European conflicts.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] The **1795 State of the Union Address** was delivered by the first president of the United States, George Washington, to a joint session of the 4th United States Congress on December 8, 1795.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] This address covered a broad range of topics, including foreign relations, military affairs, and the domestic state of the Union.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] Washington began by celebrating the peace agreement made with the Native American tribes north of the Ohio River, known as the Treaty of Greenville, ending a long and costly war.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] He emphasized that the satisfaction of the tribes had been a key objective of the treaty to ensure lasting tranquility.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] Additionally, Washington discussed ongoing peace negotiations with Algiers and the recognition of the United States' treaty by the Emperor of Morocco.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] He also noted the progress of negotiations with Spain and the recently signed Jay Treaty with Great Britain.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] Washington praised the economic prosperity of the nation, highlighting the rapid growth of population, agriculture, commerce, and manufacturing, as well as the neutral stance maintained by the United States amid conflicts in Europe.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] He attributed the country's success to the stability provided by its Constitution and encouraged Congress to continue to nurture the nation's advantages.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] The president also acknowledged the resolution of the Whiskey Rebellion and noted that the misled citizens had returned to lawfulness, allowing him to extend pardons to those involved.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1795-state-of-the-union-address] He emphasized the need for military and militia reform to ensure national security and the continued protection of frontier inhabitants from lawless attacks against Native Americans.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1796-state-of-the-union-address] The **1796 State of the Union Address** was given by George Washington, the first president of the United States, on Wednesday, December 7, 1796.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1796-state-of-the-union-address] It was given in Congress Hall, Philadelphia.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1796-state-of-the-union-address] The President also noted negotiations with the Creek Nation regarding purchase of land, which had stalled at that time.
[src:1794-state-of-the-union-address/1796-state-of-the-union-address] The President also recommended the establishment of an official military academy noting that a nation should "never be without an adequate stock of military knowledge for emergencies".
